Suppose that $\hat{u} \in F_u \cup F_{u'}$ and $v \in N_{uu'}$, i.e.~$v$ is a common neighbor of $u$ and $u'$. We will show that $\hat{u} \sim v$, thus proving the first claim. For contradiction, assume that $\hat{u} \not\sim v$. Without loss of generality we may assume that $\hat{u} \in F_u$. Note that this implies that $\hat{u} \ne v$, and so $\hat{u} \not\simeq v$. From our assumptions, we have that $\varphi(\hat{u}) = \varphi(u) \sim \varphi(v)$. This implies that $v \in D_{\hat{u}}$. Since $\varphi(\hat{u}) = \varphi(u) \not\simeq \varphi(u')$, we can apply Lemma~\ref{lem:Duu'} to conclude that $v \not\simeq u'$. Of course, this is a contradiction to the assumption that $v \in N_{uu'}$.



Now consider distinct $v_1, v_2 \in F_u \cup F_{u'}$. By the above we have that both $v_1$ and $v_2$ are adjacent to every vertex of $N_{uu'}$, and thus $N_{uu'} \subseteq N_{v_1 v_2}$. Since $\varphi(u) \not\simeq \varphi(u')$, any two distinct vertices in $F_u \cup F_{u'}$ are non-adjacent. Therefore, $|N_{uu'}| = \mu = |N_{v_1 v_2}|$ since $G$ is strongly regular. Together this implies that $N_{v_1 v_2} = N_{uu'}$.{\qed\vspace{.2cm}}



















The above lemmas already seem to place substantial restrictions on homomorphisms between strongly regular graphs, but we are not done yet. Using Lemma~\ref{lem:savior} we are able to prove the following crucial, if somewhat inscrutable, lemma.

\begin{lemma}\label{lem:duv}
Let $G$ and $H$ both be $SRG(n,k,{\lambda},{\mu})$'s and let $\varphi$ be a homomorphism from $G$ to $H$. Suppose that $\varphi(u) \not\simeq \varphi(u')$ and let $v$ be a common neighbor of $u$ and $u'$. If $x$ is a common non-neighbor of $u$ and $v$, then $\varphi(x) \not\simeq \varphi(u)$.
\end{lemma}
\proof
First note that by Lemma~\ref{lem:savior}, we have that $v$ is adjacent to every vertex of $F_u$. Therefore $\varphi(x) \ne \varphi(u)$. Thus we only have to show that $\varphi(x) \not\sim \varphi(u)$. Since $x \not\simeq u$, it suffices to show that $x \not\in D_u$. To do this we compute $(X(A - \tau I))_{uv}$ which must be 0. Note that $v \not\in D_u$ and, as mentioned, $v$ is adjacent to every element of $F_u$. Therefore, using Equation~(\ref{eqn:entries}) and Lemma~\ref{lem:thetafibres}, we have that

Since $D_{uv}$ is always a subset of $D_u$ by definition, we have that $D_u = D_{uv} := D_u \cap N_{v}$. This implies that every element of $D_u$ is adjacent to $v$. Since we assumed that $x$ is a non-neighbor of $v$, we have that $x \not\in D_u$.{\qed\vspace{.2cm}}




Note that we could not have proven the above lemma immediately using only the fact that $(X(A - \tau I))_{uv} = 0$. We first needed Lemma~\ref{lem:savior} to tell us that, under our assumptions, $v$ is adjacent to every element of $F_u$. We also made use of Lemma~\ref{lem:thetafibres}.

We are now able to prove the final lemma we will need for our main result.

\begin{lemma}\label{lem:fibre1}
Let $G$ and $H$ both be primitive $SRG(n,k,{\lambda},{\mu})$'s and let $\varphi$ be a homomorphism from $G$ to $H$. If $u,u' \in V(G)$ and $\varphi(u) \not\simeq \varphi(u')$, then $f_u = 1$.
\end{lemma}
\proof
Suppose not. Then there exists a vertex $\hat{u} \in F_u$ such that $\hat{u} \ne u$. Since $G$ is strongly regular there exists a vertex $v$ that is a common neighbor of $u$ and $u'$. Consider a common non-neighbor, $x$, of $u$ and $v$ (so $x$ is a common \emph{neighbor} of $u$ and $v$ in $\overline{G}$ which always exists since there are ${\bar{{\mu}}} \ge 1$ of them). By Lemma~\ref{lem:duv} we have that $\varphi(x) \not\simeq \varphi(u)$. Applying Lemma~\ref{lem:savior}, we have that $N_{xu} = N_{u\hat{u}}$ since $\{x,u\}, \{u,\hat{u}\} \subseteq F_u \cup F_x$.  However, Lemma~\ref{lem:savior} also implies that $v$ is adjacent to everything in $F_u$. Therefore we have that $v \in N_{u\hat{u}} = N_{xu}$. This is a contradiction to the assumption that $x$ was a non-neighbor of $v$.{\qed\vspace{.2cm}}



































\section{Main Result}

Here we combine the results of the previous section to prove our main result.

\begin{theorem}\label{thm:main}
Let $G$ and $H$ both be primitive $SRG(n,k,{\lambda},{\mu})$'s and let $\varphi$ be a homomorphism from $G$ to $H$. Then $\varphi$ is a coloring or an isomorphism.
\end{theorem}
\proof
We first show that if $f_u = 1$, then $f_v = 1$ for all $v \not\simeq u$. Suppose that $f_u = 1$. Then by Lemma~\ref{lem:thetafibres}, we have that $d_u = {\theta} (f_u - 1) = 0$ and thus $D_u = \varnothing$. Since $f_u = 1$ also implies that $F_u \setminus \{u\} = \varnothing$, we have that $\varphi(v) \not\simeq \varphi(u)$ for all $v \not\simeq u$. Applying Lemma~\ref{lem:fibre1}, we obtain $f_v = 1$ for all $v \not\simeq u$ and thus we have proven the claim.

Now we prove the theorem. If $\varphi$ is a coloring then we are done, so suppose that it is not. This is equivalent to there being $u,u' \in V(G)$ such that $\varphi(u) \not\simeq \varphi(u')$. Applying Lemma~\ref{lem:fibre1} again, we see that $f_u = 1$. By the above claim and the fact that $\overline{G}$ is connected, we have that $f_v = 1$ for all $v \in V(G)$, i.e.~that $\varphi$ is injective. Since $G$ and $H$ have the same number of vertices and edges, this proves that $\varphi$ is an isomorphism.{\qed\vspace{.2cm}}


As a corollary we obtain the following strengthening of the Cameron \& Kazanidis conjecture:

\begin{corollary}\label{cor:C&K}
Every primitive strongly regular graph is a pseudocore.
\end{corollary}


























